Aura Component Apex Controller acts as a server-side controller for your Lightning component, enabling it to interact with Salesforce data and business logic via Apex methods. 

Association: You associate an Apex class with your Aura component using the controller attribute in the <aura:component> tag, e.g., controller="MyApexController". 
Method Requirements: Apex methods exposed to the component must be:
Annotated with @AuraEnabled.
Static, public, or global. 
Calling Methods: In the component's JavaScript controller, use component.get("c.methodName") to get a reference to the server-side action, then use action.setParams() to pass parameters and action.setCallback() to handle the response. 
Execution: Use $A.enqueueAction(action) to send the request to the server. The request is processed asynchronously, and the callback function is invoked upon response. 
Error Handling: Check response.getState() in the callback to handle SUCCESS, ERROR, or INCOMPLETE states. Use response.getError() to retrieve error details. 
Key Point: Avoid naming conflicts—do not use the same name for a JavaScript controller method and an Apex method, as this can cause the JavaScript method to be called instead of the Apex method, leading to hard-to-debug issues.

1. Apex Class - AccountController 

public class AccountController {
	@AuraEnabled
    public static List<Account> getAccounts () {
        List<Account> accList = new List<Account>();
        accList = [SELECT Id, Name FROM Account LIMIT 10];
        return accList;
    }
}

2. Lightning Component - AccountData

<aura:component implements="flexipage:availableForAllPageTypes" access="global" controller = "AccountController">
    <aura:attribute name = "accList" type = "List" />
    <aura:handler name = "init" value = "{!this}" action = "{!c.doInit}" />
    <lightning:select name="select1" label="Select an Account" required="true">
        <option value="null">None</option>
        <aura:iteration items = "{!v.accList}" var = "item">
            <option value="{!item.id}">{!item.Name}</option>
        </aura:iteration>
    </lightning:select>
</aura:component>

3. Lightning Component Controller - accountDataController

({
	doInit : function(component, event, helper) {
		var action = component.get("c.getAccounts");
        action.setCallback(this, function(response) {
            var state = response.getState();
            if(state === "SUCCESS") {
                component.set("v.accList", response.getReturnValue());
            }
        });
        $A.enqueueAction(action);
	}
})

